## Before Writing Code

1. Call `rules_list_categories` to see available rule categories.
2. Call `rules_get_by_category` for the relevant categories:
   - `code_style` and `architecture` for new features
   - `testing` when writing tests
   - `libraries` when choosing dependencies
3. Call `decisions_search` with relevant keywords to check for prior decisions in the same domain.

## Working on Tickets

- When starting work on a ticket, use the **`ticket_to_plan`** prompt to assemble full context (ticket details, related docs, applicable rules, past decisions) in one step.
- For quick ticket references encountered in text, use `jira_resolve_link` instead of the full `jira_get_ticket`.

## During Code Review

- Use the **`code_review_checklist`** prompt to generate a language-specific review checklist from your rules.

## Writing Documentation

- Use the **`write_tech_doc`** prompt to scaffold a Confluence technical document from a ticket's context.

## Working with Merge Requests

- Use `gitlab_create_mr` to create a new MR from the current branch. If `default_project` is configured, omit the `project` parameter.
- Use `gitlab_list_mrs` to see open MRs before creating a new one (avoid duplicates).
- Use `gitlab_mr_diff` to review changes in an MR before adding comments.
- Use `gitlab_add_mr_comment` to post review feedback or status updates.
- For quick MR references encountered in text (e.g. `!42` or a GitLab URL), use `gitlab_resolve_link`.

## Working with Pull Requests (GitHub)

- Use `github_create_pr` to create a new PR. If `default_repo` is configured (owner/repo), omit the `repo` parameter.
- Use `github_list_prs` to see open PRs before creating a new one (avoid duplicates).
- Use `github_pr_diff` to review changes in a PR before adding comments.
- Use `github_add_pr_comment` to post review feedback or status updates.
- For quick PR references encountered in text (e.g. `#42` or a GitHub PR URL), use `github_resolve_link`.

## Link Resolution

- When encountering a Jira ticket key (e.g. `PROJ-123`) in text, use `jira_resolve_link` for quick context.
- When encountering a Confluence URL or page ID, use `confluence_resolve_link` for quick context.
- When encountering a GitLab MR reference (e.g. `!42`) or URL, use `gitlab_resolve_link` for quick context.
- When encountering a GitHub PR reference (e.g. `#42`) or URL, use `github_resolve_link` for quick context.

## Session Context

- Store frequently-referenced values (current ticket, branch, sprint) via `context_set` to avoid redundant API calls.
- Use `context_get` to recall stored values before making Jira/Confluence calls.

## Configuration

- Use `config_get` to check which integrations are enabled and what the active settings are.
